wizard_pre_create_tenant() {
	wizard_pre_message "
    Would it be a good idea to put all your files at the root folder of your storage system? In most case, no, right? It would be even worst if some of those files were about the same thing but on different contexts. You would have to name each file with the full context to make them findable later. That's why we distribute them in directories in a folder hierarchy. Each entry in the hierarchy represents an specific context, which allows you to do '/Company A/Proof of Payment.pdf' instead of 'Proof of Payment for Company A.pdf'.

    This is what Tenants are about. They are organizations units that allows you to isolate resources in different contexts.

    You can give Tenants any semantics you want, just like you do in your file system. However, the most common use case for Tenants is the creation of customer specific contexts in such a way that everything related to one particular customer is isolated from other's.

    So, for example, let's say walt.id has a managed Enterprise instance that is shared by multiple customers. Each customer would be a separated Tenant in the platform. I'll show you.

    Press any key to create an specific \"folder\" for your brand new customer Acme Corporations...

        $cli_name create-tenant
	"
}

wizard_pos_create_tenant() {
	wizard_pos_message "
    Cool. The '$TENANT' tenant has been successfully created.

    You can learn more about Tenants here:

    https://docs.walt.id/enterprise-stack/administration/tenants/overview

    Btw, have you seen the tenant id? It's '$ROOT_ORGANIZATION.mycustomer'. It follows the rule <organization_name>.<tenant_name>. Get used to it. This structure will be used everywhere from now on to reference services and other resources.

    We will now start creating the services needed to issue and verify credentials. All of them will be created inside the 'MyCustomer' tenant. Why? Just because we want those services to be customer specific. 
    
    By doing this, in addition to the security isolation that is created between the environments of each customer, preventing one customer from accessing the services of another, it also becomes possible to customize the services to the specifics of each of them.
	"
}

